# Build output that may appear inside an example dir during local
# verification. Per-language conventions vary; this is a superset.
build/
_build/
dist/
target/
bin/
obj/
*.exe
*.dll
*.so
*.dylib
*.a
*.o
*.obj
.repro/
.reprobuild/
node_modules/
__pycache__/
*.pyc
.venv/
venv/
nimcache/
.nimcache/
*.gem
.bundle/
Gemfile.lock
package-lock.json
yarn.lock
pnpm-lock.yaml
Cargo.lock
# M6 build-rs fixture: the crude action invokes
# ``cargo build --release --locked --offline`` so the lockfile MUST be
# committed for reproducibility. Without this negation rule the global
# ``Cargo.lock`` ignore above would force the fixture maintainer to
# ``git add -f`` on every lockfile bump, which silently rots.
!rust/binary-with-build-rs/Cargo.lock
# M23 binary-with-crates-io fixture: same crude path as the M6 build-rs
# fixture (``cargo build --release --locked --offline``), so the
# lockfile MUST be committed for reproducibility. The Mode B fallback
# resolves the libc dep against the host CARGO_HOME registry but
# refuses to run without the locked Cargo.lock.
!rust/binary-with-crates-io/Cargo.lock
# M8 typescript-cli fixture: the JS/TS convention spec places CLI
# entry points at ``src/bin/<name>.ts`` (committed source). Without
# this negation the global ``bin/`` ignore above swallows the
# directory and the fixture loses its entry point.
!javascript-typescript/typescript-cli/src/bin/
!javascript-typescript/typescript-cli/src/bin/**
# M21 typescript-cli fixture: the JS/TS convention's A1 ``npm ci``
# action requires a committed ``package-lock.json`` for reproducibility
# (npm ci refuses to run without the lockfile). The global
# ``package-lock.json`` ignore above is the right default for app
# fixtures whose convention falls back to ``npx --yes`` on-demand; the
# typescript-cli fixture deliberately opts into the A1 path so the
# lockfile must be tracked.
!javascript-typescript/typescript-cli/package-lock.json
.gradle/
.idea/
.vscode/
